An Act to reform the parole board.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General Court assembled, and by the authority
of the same, as follows:
1 SECTION 1. Section 4 of chapter 27 of the General Laws, as appearing in the 2022
2 Official Edition, is hereby amended by striking out the third and fourth paragraphs and inserting
3 in place thereof the following 2 paragraphs:-
4 The governor shall designate 1 of the members as chair, said member to serve as chair at
5 the will of the governor. In the case of the absence or disability of the chair, the governor may
6 designate 1 of the members to act as chair during such absence or disability.
7 The salary of each member of the board shall be equal to 80 per cent of the salary paid to
8 the chief justice of the trial court. Members shall devote full time to their duties. No member
9 shall hold any other salaried public office or engage in any activity in violation of any law or that
10 interferes or conflicts with the member’s full-time service as a member during their incumbency.
11 SECTION 2. Said chapter 27 is hereby further amended by inserting after section 4 the
12 following section:-
1 of 5

13 Section 4A. (a) The parole board shall employ an executive director. The executive
14 director shall serve at the pleasure of the board and shall report to the board through the
15 chairperson. The salary of the executive director shall be equal to the salary paid to the chief
16 justice of the trial court.
17 (b) The executive director shall be responsible for all administrative, operational and
18 financial functions of the board, including but not limited to:
19 (i) employing subject to appropriation and the requirements of chapter 30 and
20 chapter 31 an executive secretary and such hearing officers, clerks, attorneys and other
21 employees and consultants as the work of the parole board may require;
22 (ii) overseeing the day-to-day operations of the board;
23 (iii) managing the preparation and administration of the board's budget;
24 (iv) administering human resources functions for the board;
25 (v) make rules relative to the conduct of its employees in the performance of their
26 duties;
27 (vi) overseeing information technology services for the board;
28 (vii) directing facility operations and maintenance.
29 (viii) ensuring compliance with all applicable laws and regulations; and
30 (ix) performing other duties as assigned by the board.
31 (c) The chairperson of the board shall retain authority and responsibility for:
2 of 5

32 (i) directing assignments of members of the board;
33 (ii) establishing policies for parole decisions;”
34 (iii) presiding over board meetings;
35 (iv) coordinating with other agencies on policy matters; and
36 (v) other duties as provided by law.
