50 SECTION 6. Said chapter 27, as so appearing, is hereby further amended by inserting
51 after section 5 the following section:-
3 of 5

52 Section 5A. (a) Notwithstanding any general or special law to the contrary, the parole
53 board may conduct any parole hearings and other board meetings through remote means,
54 including but not limited to telephonic or video conferencing technology provided that: (1) all
55 participants have access to the technology necessary to participate; (2) the identity of each
56 participant can be verified; (3) the public has access to observe any public portions of the
57 proceedings in accordance with section 20 of chapter 30A; (4) the remote technology provides
58 for clear audio and, where applicable, visual communication among all participants; and (5) the
59 board establishes procedures to ensure that the rights of prisoners, paroled prisoners and victims
60 to participate meaningfully in parole hearings are preserved.
61 (b) The board shall adopt regulations governing the use of remote meetings, which shall
62 include procedures for: (1) providing notice to all participants; (2) maintaining the confidentiality
63 of information as required by law; (3) recording and maintaining records of the proceedings; and
64 (4) addressing technical difficulties that may arise during remote proceedings.
65 (c) The executive director shall ensure that the board has the technical resources
66 necessary to conduct remote meetings effectively.
67 SECTION 7. Section 133A of chapter 127 of the General Laws, as so appearing, is
68 hereby amended by striking out, in lines 12 to 14 inclusive, the words “the full membership” and
69 inserting in place thereof the following words:- a majority of the board.
70 SECTION 8. The parole board shall develop and implement a transition plan for
71 separating the positions of chairperson and executive director to allow for a smooth transition of
72 administrative functions from the chairperson to the executive director. The transition plan shall
73 include:
4 of 5

74 (a) developing position descriptions, responsibilities and qualifications for the
75 chairperson and executive director positions to ensure the duties are distinct and appropriate for
76 each position;
77 (b) creating a formalized process for selecting the executive director;
78 (c) establishing time frames for completing transition activities;
79 (d) developing protocols for communication between the chairperson and executive
80 director; and
81 (e) identifying necessary amendments to existing statutes, regulations and policies.
82 SECTION 9. The parole board shall complete the transition plan required by section 8
83 within 90 days after the effective date of this act and shall implement the transition plan within
84 180 days after the effective date of this act.
85 SECTION 10. The parole board shall file a report with the clerks of the house of
86 representatives and the senate, the joint committee on public safety and homeland security, and
87 the house and senate committees on ways and means detailing the implementation of this act not
88 later than 1 year after the effective date of this act.
